          "label": "<p>If a tumour blocked the left foramen of Monro, which ventricle would dilate?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>If a tumour blocked the left foramen of Monro, which ventricle would dilate?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Both lateral ventricles equally</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Only the left foramen is blocked. The right lateral ventricle drains normally through its own patent foramen of Monro and does not dilate.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The third ventricle</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The third ventricle lies downstream of the block. It continues to drain via the aqueduct of Sylvius and does not dilate from this obstruction.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The left lateral ventricle only</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The foramen of Monro is the sole exit from each lateral ventricle. Blocking it on one side traps CSF upstream, dilating only the ipsilateral lateral ventricle.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The fourth ventricle</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The fourth ventricle is two passages downstream (beyond the third ventricle and aqueduct of Sylvius). It is unobstructed and does not dilate.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Recall the CSF flow sequence: lateral ventricle → foramen of Monro → third ventricle → aqueduct of Sylvius → fourth ventricle. Blockage traps fluid upstream of the obstruction, so only the left lateral ventricle dilates."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Each lateral ventricle drains exclusively through its own foramen of Monro into the third ventricle. Unilateral blockage causes ipsilateral ventricular dilatation — an important principle when interpreting obstructive hydrocephalus on imaging."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
