          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient with a pituitary tumour develops loss of both temporal visual fields (bitemporal hemianopia). Which fibres are damaged at the optic chiasm?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Temporal retinal fibres, which remain ipsilateral at the chiasm</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Temporal retinal fibres carry nasal (inner) visual field signals and do not cross at the chiasm. A midline tumour compressing from below does not selectively affect these uncrossed fibres.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>All fibres in the optic nerve proximal to the chiasm</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Complete optic nerve damage causes monocular blindness in one eye, not bilateral temporal field loss.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Nasal retinal fibres, which cross at the chiasm</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Nasal retinal fibres carry temporal visual field signals and cross to the opposite side at the chiasm. A pituitary tumour compresses these crossing fibres from below, selectively removing the temporal field of both eyes.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Fibres in Meyer's loop within the temporal lobe</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Meyer's loop is the inferior portion of the optic radiations in the temporal lobe, far from the chiasm. Damage there causes a contralateral superior quadrantanopia ('pie in the sky'), not bitemporal hemianopia.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember the chiasm crossing rule from this scene: nasal retinal fibres cross to the opposite side at the chiasm, while temporal retinal fibres stay on the same side. A midline pituitary tumour compresses the crossing nasal fibres, removing the temporal visual field bilaterally."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "The chiasm crossing rule predicts every visual field defect: nasal retinal fibres (carrying temporal field signals) cross, while temporal fibres stay ipsilateral. This single principle explains bitemporal hemianopia from chiasm lesions and homonymous hemianopia from post-chiasmal lesions."
                }
              ],
